snippet.textDisplay:
You can tell that Papa John is a down to earth man that solely cares about his employees, the quality of the product and his name. The dark side of the corporate world ate him up and he wasn't prepared because he probably didn't think something this dirty could happen to him.

Ultimately Papa John's will suffer tremendously without having a real pizza man in that board room. Those people are just empty suits and terrible human beings. They don't care about the pizza, the quality, their reputation, or employees. They only care about the numbers, they can't cook a pizza, don't know the first thing about the cooking side and probably have never been in a Papa John's franchise.

In the end Papa John's needs Papa. He's the face and is the only one that can fix this quality control issue. I also hope the truth comes out and he clears his name because you can tell it's really eating him up.

10 Point Papa Podcast Score: 4/10

Although ingredients are fresh and recipe is good... Jokes need more proofing, questions are flat and dry, interruptions need cutting, and delivery needs a lot of improvement.

Another great guest podcast almost ruined by Ethan's constant interruptions and endless bad joke attempts.

It's like he's so preoccupied with trying to get thru his list of questions and satisfy his obnoxious need to inject off the mark bad jokes, that he is obviously not listening when the guest is answering.

Papa John with the "Let me finish" smack down is the highlight of this podcast.
